# NestJS Microservices — Cursor Rules

**Stack**: NestJS 11.0.1 | PostgreSQL + Prisma 7.3.0 | Jest + Supertest | pnpm

---

## Project Overview

This is a NestJS monorepo with a microservices architecture. HTTP traffic enters through `api-gateway` (port 9011), which validates requests and proxies them over TCP to `auth-service` (port 9012). Only `auth-service` touches the database.

```
nestjs-starter/
├── apps/
│   ├── api-gateway/     # HTTP server (port 9011) — thin proxy, guards, Swagger
│   └── auth-service/    # TCP microservice (port 9012) — Auth + Users domains
├── libs/
│   ├── common/          # @app/common — pipes, filters, decorators, DTOs, utils
│   ├── prisma/          # @app/prisma — PrismaModule, PrismaService
│   └── contracts/       # @app/contracts — message patterns + payload interfaces
└── prisma/              # Shared Prisma schema
```

**Request flow:**
```
Client → HTTP → api-gateway (ApiKeyGuard → JwtAuthGuard → RolesGuard) → TCP → auth-service → PostgreSQL
```

**Port allocation**: api-gateway=9011 (HTTP), auth-service=9012 (TCP). Future services increment from 9013.

---

## Core Architecture Rules

### Service Boundaries

- `api-gateway` is an HTTP proxy. It has no database access and no business logic.
- `auth-service` owns all business logic, validation, and data persistence.
- `@app/prisma` is only imported in `apps/auth-service/src/app.module.ts`. Never in the gateway.
- Shared code always goes in `libs/`. Never duplicate utilities across apps.

### Layer Separation

| Layer | Lives In | Responsibility |
|---|---|---|
| Gateway Controller | `apps/api-gateway/src/<feature>/` | HTTP routing, extract from request, `ClientProxy.send()` |
| Auth-service Controller | `apps/auth-service/src/<feature>/` | `@MessagePattern` handlers, delegate to service |
| Service | `apps/auth-service/src/<feature>/` | Business logic, validation, throw HTTP exceptions |
| Repository | `apps/auth-service/src/<feature>/` | Prisma queries only — no logic |
| Contracts | `libs/contracts/src/` | Patterns, payloads — shared between gateway and auth-service |

### TCP Communication Pattern

Gateway sends a message with `ClientProxy.send(PATTERN, payload)` and awaits the response with `firstValueFrom()`. Auth-service handles it with `@MessagePattern(PATTERN)`.

```typescript
// Gateway controller (HTTP proxy — no business logic)
@Get('me')
getCurrentUser(@User() user: AuthorizedUser): Promise<CurrentUserResponseDto> {
  return firstValueFrom(
    this.authClient.send(AUTH_PATTERNS.ME, { context: user }),
  );
}

// Auth-service controller (TCP handler — delegates to service)
@MessagePattern(AUTH_PATTERNS.ME)
getMe(@Payload() { context }: { context: AuthContext }): Promise<CurrentUserResponseDto> {
  return this.authService.getMe(context.accountId);
}
```

### `MicroservicesClientModule` — Global Client DI

`AUTH_SERVICE` `ClientProxy` is registered once in `apps/api-gateway/src/microservices-client.module.ts` using `@Global()`. All gateway feature modules inject `@Inject(AUTH_SERVICE) authClient: ClientProxy` without importing `ClientsModule` themselves.

When adding a new microservice, add its client to `MicroservicesClientModule` — **never** register `ClientsModule` inside a feature module.

### JWT — Self-Contained Payload (No TCP Hop Per Request)

JWT tokens embed `name`, `roleId`, `roleName`, and `organizationId` at sign-in time. The gateway's `JwtStrategy` validates tokens locally — no TCP call to auth-service on every request. When updating `auth.service.ts` signing logic, always include all user context fields in the payload.

### Error Propagation Across TCP

Auth-service services throw NestJS HTTP exceptions (`NotFoundException`, `ConflictException`, etc.). These are serialized as `RpcException` over TCP. The gateway's global `RpcExceptionFilter` (`libs/common/src/filters/rpc-exception.filter.ts`) unwraps them back to HTTP responses with the correct status code. Never throw `RpcException` directly from services.

